Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Sun Resorts; Sterling Bank of Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-12T15:54:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-12/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-sun-resorts-sterling-bank-of-nigeria.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped 1.7
percent to 61.98 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest
level since Feb. 17, 2010.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  advanced for a second
day, increasing 1.8 percent to 769.64 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange  All-Share Index jumped 1.7
percent to 22,775.55 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to a statement on the bourse’s website. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index
rose 0.5 percent to 1,945.94 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port
Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index climbed for a
second day, gaining 0.4 percent to 1,180.77 by the 3 p.m. close
in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Harel Freres Ltd. (HFRERES)  , a Mauritian company with
interests in sugar and energy, advanced 0.5 rupees, or 1.3
percent, to 38.20 rupees, the highest close since Aug. 4, after
the company said its loss narrowed in the second quarter as
revenue advanced and it forecast an improved performance for the
remainder of the year.  Kenya Reinsurance Corp. (KNRE KN), the state run reinsurer,
climbed 20 cents, or 2.5 percent, to 8.25 shillings, the biggest
gain since Aug. 1, after the company said first-half profit rose
15 percent as premiums increased.  Sun Resorts Ltd. (SUN MP), Mauritius’s second-biggest
leisure operator, declined 1 rupee, or 1.8 percent, to 55
rupees, after its loss widened in the second quarter as the low
tourism season was exacerbated by a debt crisis in  Europe , the
country’s main source of visitors.  Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender, gained
2 kobo, or 1.4 percent, to 1.44 naira, after it agreed to buy
privately held Equitorial Trust Bank, a lender bailed out by the
central bank in 2009, Sterling said in a statement published
today on the website of the Nigerian Stock Exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
